## Why This Question Is Asked

This question evaluates system design proficiency for cross-language NLP with strict privacy and real-time performance constraints. It also tests understanding of knowledge graph integration and disaster recovery mechanisms.

## Key Concepts

- **Streaming multilingual NER**: Continuous entity extraction across 25 languages in real-time
- **Cross-language alias resolution**: Linking entities across different languages to a canonical form
- **Privacy-preserving per-tenant embeddings**: Isolated embedding spaces that prevent data leakage between tenants
- **Edge-friendly inference**: Lightweight models deployable close to data sources for minimal latency
- **Knowledge graph drift and rollback**: Tracking schema/behavior changes with the ability to revert safely

## Architecture Overview

```javascript
// Streaming pipeline architecture
async function processIncidentReport(text, tenant, metadata) {
  const normalized = await normalize(text);
  const entities = await runMultilingualNER(normalized, tenant);
  const linked = await resolveCrossLingualAliases(entities, sharedIndex);
  await updateKnowledgeGraph(linked, tenant, metadata);
  return { entities, aliases, confidence };
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you evaluate cross-language alias accuracy across diverse language pairs?
- What rollback strategies would you implement for knowledge graph inconsistencies?
- How would you detect and handle model drift in production?
- What privacy guarantees do per-tenant embeddings provide against inference attacks?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests end-to-end design for high-stakes, multilingual NLP with strict latency, privacy, and governance constraints. Probes integration of retrieval-augmented detection, on-device preprocessing, drift-aware evaluation, explainability, and safe rollout strategies.

## Key Concepts

- Real-time streaming NLP
- Retrieval-augmented detection
- On-device PII redaction
- Multilingual DistilBERT variants
- Drift detection and governance
- Explainability and audit logging

## Code Example

```javascript
// Pseudocode for pipeline steps
async function infer(text, lang) {
  const redacted = redactPII(text, lang)
  const ctx = encode(redacted, lang)
  const evidence = retriever.search(redacted, lang)
  const score = detector.score(ctx, evidence)
  return { score, evidence }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you measure and bound the false positive rate across languages?
- How would you implement the rollback and audit logging in production?
